that I've been painting.

00:32:47.486 --> 00:32:48.506 A:middle
And they can be scaled

00:32:48.946 --> 00:32:50.906 A:middle
to whatever amount
of detail you need.

00:32:50.906 --> 00:32:54.426 A:middle
So for a video game, they'd be
down at like 256 pixel squared

00:32:54.766 --> 00:32:55.516 A:middle
which is pretty small.

00:32:55.916 --> 00:32:57.226 A:middle
But for a feature film,

00:32:57.696 --> 00:32:59.876 A:middle
you never know how much
detail you're going to need.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:00.076 --> 00:33:04.226 A:middle
So these are actually 8,000
pixels by 8,000 pixels.

00:33:04.846 --> 00:33:08.556 A:middle
That's 33 times bigger
than an HD frame

00:33:08.556 --> 00:33:09.876 A:middle
from a movie, all right?

00:33:10.306 --> 00:33:12.556 A:middle
But the reason you need that
is because you never know

00:33:12.556 --> 00:33:14.546 A:middle
if the character is going to
walk right past the camera

00:33:14.876 --> 00:33:16.726 A:middle
and we're going to
see all of this detail

00:33:16.726 --> 00:33:18.296 A:middle
on one of these legs, right?

00:33:18.346 --> 00:33:19.566 A:middle
And that actually
happened in the film.

00:33:19.566 --> 00:33:21.626 A:middle
She walks right past the camera.

00:33:21.626 --> 00:33:25.066 A:middle
So we really need this level
of fidelity to make sure

00:33:25.066 --> 00:33:28.596 A:middle
that she holds up in any
situation that she shows up in.

00:33:28.676 --> 00:33:31.206 A:middle
So, the next thing I'm going
to do and the reason why I came

00:33:31.206 --> 00:33:34.956 A:middle
into this view is to show you
how I would paint her makeup.

00:33:34.956 --> 00:33:37.146 A:middle
And I painted on
the flat version

00:33:37.146 --> 00:33:38.566 A:middle
because it's a little
bit easier than trying

00:33:38.566 --> 00:33:39.816 A:middle
to work around the 3D shape.

00:33:40.136 --> 00:33:41.186 A:middle
But as I paint on the right,

00:33:41.186 --> 00:33:42.656 A:middle
you'll see that it
updates on the left.

00:33:43.576 --> 00:33:45.826 A:middle
So I'm going to grab this
great eye shadow color.

00:33:45.826 --> 00:33:49.896 A:middle
Now, a couple of weeks
ago, we had the wrap party

00:33:49.896 --> 00:33:53.546 A:middle
where the movie is-- the movie
is finished and we all go

00:33:53.546 --> 00:33:55.346 A:middle
to see it for the first
time and we dress up.

00:33:55.346 --> 00:33:57.666 A:middle
And my wife usually gets her
makeup professionally done.

00:33:57.666 --> 00:34:00.496 A:middle
But I told her, "Honey, I
painted makeup before, you know.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:33:57.666 --> 00:34:00.496 A:middle
But I told her, "Honey, I
painted makeup before, you know.

00:34:00.496 --> 00:34:02.226 A:middle
I do it for work.

00:34:02.526 --> 00:34:03.906 A:middle
It's not a big deal.

00:34:03.906 --> 00:34:04.936 A:middle
I can handle it."

00:34:05.176 --> 00:34:08.056 A:middle
So, I painted her makeup,
I painted her eye shadow.

00:34:08.056 --> 00:34:09.706 A:middle
I thought it looked
great, you know?

00:34:10.065 --> 00:34:11.286 A:middle
I thought I did this great job.

00:34:11.286 --> 00:34:15.545 A:middle
She looks in the mirror, was
not pleased with my efforts.

00:34:15.545 --> 00:34:18.946 A:middle
So, we ended up being about
half an hour late to the movie.

00:34:19.826 --> 00:34:20.846 A:middle
Well we made it before
the movie.

00:34:20.846 --> 00:34:21.976 A:middle
We're half an hour
late to the party.

00:34:22.176 --> 00:34:23.556 A:middle
So we made it for
the important part,

00:34:23.656 --> 00:34:26.755 A:middle
but I doubt she'll trust me to
do her makeup again after that.

00:34:27.676 --> 00:34:28.946 A:middle
I guess, you know, painting

00:34:28.946 --> 00:34:31.275 A:middle
on monsters doesn't
necessarily transfer directly

00:34:31.275 --> 00:34:33.516 A:middle
over to painting on humans.

00:34:34.585 --> 00:34:35.386 A:middle
Would never have guessed.

00:34:35.696 --> 00:34:38.036 A:middle
Anyway, so I'm painting
this sweet purple eye shadow

00:34:38.036 --> 00:34:38.856 A:middle
onto this character.

00:34:39.136 --> 00:34:40.485 A:middle
And you can see,
again, as I'm painting

00:34:40.485 --> 00:34:41.806 A:middle
on the right it's
updating on the left.

00:34:42.166 --> 00:34:48.456 A:middle
And-- So what we've got
here is basically two views

00:34:48.456 --> 00:34:49.196 A:middle
of the same thing.

00:34:49.916 --> 00:34:52.436 A:middle
So now I've done that, I'm
going to just go ahead and visit

00:34:52.436 --> 00:34:54.496 A:middle
on the other side of--
I've got another layer

00:34:54.496 --> 00:34:56.906 A:middle
that has her makeup
on the other side.

00:34:56.976 --> 00:34:59.406 A:middle
I always forget character
right or my right.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:00.986 --> 00:35:03.446 A:middle
Guess-- I guessed right, great.

00:35:03.686 --> 00:35:05.006 A:middle
I'm not even going to
bother with her lipstick.

00:35:05.006 --> 00:35:06.066 A:middle
Painting lipstick for me is

00:35:06.066 --> 00:35:08.066 A:middle
like when your four-year-old
daughter tries

00:35:08.066 --> 00:35:09.516 A:middle
to paint her lipstick
for the first time,

00:35:09.956 --> 00:35:11.406 A:middle
I've never gotten past

00:35:11.406 --> 00:35:13.186 A:middle
that because I just
don't do it often enough.

00:35:13.846 --> 00:35:15.846 A:middle
Anyway, so we've
got her makeup done,

00:35:15.846 --> 00:35:17.376 A:middle
and her skin color looks good.

00:35:17.666 --> 00:35:20.276 A:middle
But it's still lacking
some that detail

00:35:20.276 --> 00:35:21.366 A:middle
that we saw from the packet.

00:35:21.406 --> 00:35:23.196 A:middle
Now, this is the color channel

00:35:23.196 --> 00:35:25.396 A:middle
and I've got some nice
variety to her color.

00:35:25.846 --> 00:35:29.026 A:middle
But with every character
in a 3D film,

00:35:29.426 --> 00:35:32.076 A:middle
there are multiple channels
that define different parts

00:35:32.076 --> 00:35:33.326 A:middle
of what the character
looks like.

00:35:33.646 --> 00:35:35.196 A:middle
So this is the slide
from the shader packet

00:35:35.236 --> 00:35:37.916 A:middle
that shows me what the
characters look like,

00:35:37.986 --> 00:35:39.866 A:middle
what the character's face
looks like in more detail.

00:35:39.866 --> 00:35:42.396 A:middle
And there's some really
graphic shapes to her wrinkles

00:35:42.786 --> 00:35:46.346 A:middle
and to the, you know,
the shape of her face,

00:35:46.346 --> 00:35:47.456 A:middle
more than just the color.

00:35:47.966 --> 00:35:50.476 A:middle
And so we would actually paint
that on a separate channel.

00:35:50.476 --> 00:35:53.486 A:middle
It would be on what we call the
bump or the displacement map.

00:35:53.636 --> 00:35:56.056 A:middle
And that's a grayscale
channel that defines

00:35:56.306 --> 00:35:58.366 A:middle
where the wrinkles go in
and where things bump out.

00:35:58.776 --> 00:36:01.686 A:middle
And so, I'm going to show you
how I would do that over here.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:35:58.776 --> 00:36:01.686 A:middle
And so, I'm going to show you
how I would do that over here.

00:36:04.676 --> 00:36:06.986 A:middle
So, here we're starting with a
color and I'm going to switch

00:36:06.986 --> 00:36:09.196 A:middle
over to the bump channel.

00:36:09.816 --> 00:36:11.976 A:middle
It starts out with this--

00:36:12.176 --> 00:36:14.176 A:middle
you know, just this
gray solid image.

00:36:14.286 --> 00:36:18.276 A:middle
And the first thing I'm going
to do is flood in some texture,

00:36:18.316 --> 00:36:22.366 A:middle
flood in just this
basic leather variety.

00:36:22.366 --> 00:36:25.756 A:middle
Now, it looks good but it
doesn't have the specificity

00:36:25.756 --> 00:36:29.176 A:middle
that we'd really want for this
character to match that artwork,

00:36:29.176 --> 00:36:30.086 A:middle
that beautiful artwork.

00:36:31.506 --> 00:36:34.966 A:middle
So the first thing that I'm
going to do is actually bring

00:36:34.966 --> 00:36:36.166 A:middle
in a picture of an elephant.

00:36:36.296 --> 00:36:39.246 A:middle
So this is the side of an
elephant as you can see.

00:36:40.116 --> 00:36:43.756 A:middle
And I'm actually going to
use that to paint through

00:36:43.756 --> 00:36:46.816 A:middle
and get some wrinkles on the
surface of this character.

00:36:46.816 --> 00:36:48.026 A:middle
So I'm going to start
with her eye.

00:36:49.196 --> 00:36:52.936 A:middle
And I'm trying to find the right
angle to paint through because

00:36:53.296 --> 00:36:55.626 A:middle
with wrinkles, if you look at
some with really wrinkly skin,

00:36:55.626 --> 00:36:57.376 A:middle
none of the wrinkles
are arbitrary.

00:36:57.376 --> 00:37:01.216 A:middle
All of them flow exactly
where the skin would fold

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:36:57.376 --> 00:37:01.216 A:middle
All of them flow exactly
where the skin would fold

00:37:01.216 --> 00:37:02.366 A:middle
and compress over time.

00:37:02.966 --> 00:37:05.516 A:middle
And so, I can't just
paint these willy-nilly.

00:37:05.516 --> 00:37:06.656 A:middle
I have to really make sure

00:37:06.656 --> 00:37:09.906 A:middle
that they are feeling what we
would call motivated, right?

00:37:09.946 --> 00:37:12.666 A:middle
That they would be--
they would be naturally

00:37:12.666 --> 00:37:14.216 A:middle
where the character
would be wrinkling.

00:37:14.216 --> 00:37:15.846 A:middle
Now, this is obviously
a made up character.

00:37:15.846 --> 00:37:18.236 A:middle
But the character still has
to feel believable, right?

00:37:18.296 --> 00:37:20.726 A:middle
If this character
creature were to exist,

00:37:21.366 --> 00:37:22.726 A:middle
how would she wrinkle
in her face?

00:37:22.956 --> 00:37:25.086 A:middle
So, I'm good with these.

00:37:25.216 --> 00:37:26.716 A:middle
I'm going to zoom out.

00:37:26.716 --> 00:37:27.456 A:middle
And this is one of my--

00:37:28.016 --> 00:37:30.526 A:middle
it's really one of my
favorite features in MARI

00:37:30.576 --> 00:37:34.166 A:middle
because I can get so much detail
so rapidly onto the character.

00:37:34.596 --> 00:37:36.396 A:middle
And so I'm just going to paint
some of these wrinkles in.

00:37:36.396 --> 00:37:38.486 A:middle
And again, since this is
the black and white map,

00:37:38.936 --> 00:37:40.436 A:middle
it's really hard to tell
it how this is going

00:37:40.436 --> 00:37:42.216 A:middle
to affect the final
look of the character.

00:37:42.506 --> 00:37:43.706 A:middle
And I'll get more
into that later.

00:37:43.766 --> 00:37:46.286 A:middle
But this is, you know,
this is where we start

00:37:46.366 --> 00:37:49.156 A:middle
from in getting a lot
of this detail in.

00:37:49.386 --> 00:37:51.596 A:middle
There's this great spot on
the texture that looks just

00:37:51.596 --> 00:37:54.136 A:middle
like forehead, if I can find it.

00:37:54.916 --> 00:37:56.586 A:middle
Right about-- I'm upside down.

00:37:56.756 --> 00:37:57.716 A:middle
There we go.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:02.546 --> 00:38:04.656 A:middle
So the next image that I'm
actually going to pull in came

00:38:04.656 --> 00:38:06.486 A:middle
from a picture that
I took on my iPhone

00:38:06.486 --> 00:38:07.676 A:middle
from the Pixar parking lot.

00:38:07.676 --> 00:38:08.756 A:middle
There are these trees there.

00:38:09.086 --> 00:38:11.036 A:middle
You can the tire of
my car over here.

00:38:11.996 --> 00:38:15.746 A:middle
These trees there that spray sap
in all the cars for some reason,

00:38:15.876 --> 00:38:17.476 A:middle
and I'm not sure, you know, why.

00:38:17.476 --> 00:38:21.196 A:middle
But I was walking into work and
I saw the texture on the side

00:38:21.196 --> 00:38:23.036 A:middle
and I just stared at it,
like, you know, weirdo.

00:38:23.186 --> 00:38:23.756 A:middle
I'm like, wow.

00:38:24.426 --> 00:38:25.616 A:middle
That texture looks really cool.

00:38:25.616 --> 00:38:26.726 A:middle
I'm not sure what I'm
going to use it for.

00:38:26.726 --> 00:38:29.596 A:middle
So I took the picture and then
I realized it was actually this

00:38:29.646 --> 00:38:33.816 A:middle
really perfect way to transition
from the organic leather

00:38:33.816 --> 00:38:36.466 A:middle
on the front of her face
to the more hardened shells

00:38:36.466 --> 00:38:37.336 A:middle
on the side of her head.

00:38:37.686 --> 00:38:40.666 A:middle
So, I really loved it for
that particular purpose.

00:38:40.666 --> 00:38:41.926 A:middle
Though when I took the
picture, I had no idea

00:38:41.926 --> 00:38:45.086 A:middle
when I was going to use it.

00:38:45.266 --> 00:38:48.706 A:middle
Again, I'm trying to get sort
of this material transition

00:38:48.706 --> 00:38:51.136 A:middle
because we're talking about
two different textures here.

00:38:53.456 --> 00:38:54.786 A:middle
This, again, is one
of my favorite parts

00:38:54.786 --> 00:38:58.466 A:middle
because I can really paint in
as much detail as I would like.

00:38:59.196 --> 00:39:02.706 A:middle
Now, so we've got these shapes
and it's starting to feel good

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:38:59.196 --> 00:39:02.706 A:middle
Now, so we've got these shapes
and it's starting to feel good

00:39:02.706 --> 00:39:04.466 A:middle
but it's still in the realm

00:39:04.466 --> 00:39:06.886 A:middle
of being a bit too
photorealistic, right?

00:39:06.926 --> 00:39:10.036 A:middle
We could be moving into Uncanny
Valley here if I'm not careful

00:39:10.236 --> 00:39:12.616 A:middle
with all of this photo
detail that I'm using.

00:39:12.616 --> 00:39:16.296 A:middle
And so, the next thing that
I would do is actually start

00:39:16.296 --> 00:39:20.146 A:middle
to paint on top of this
to really nail the details

00:39:20.146 --> 00:39:23.276 A:middle
down the way that-- the way
that it was in the art packet.

00:39:24.836 --> 00:39:27.126 A:middle
So, let's see.

00:39:27.486 --> 00:39:31.176 A:middle
I remember from the packet there
were these really graphic shapes

00:39:31.176 --> 00:39:31.876 A:middle
around her eyes.

00:39:31.876 --> 00:39:33.276 A:middle
I'm going to try
and pull those out.

00:39:33.666 --> 00:39:35.986 A:middle
Again, like I said, I'm
going pretty darn fast here.

00:39:35.986 --> 00:39:43.716 A:middle
So, I apologize I'm being a
bit sloppy in how I do this.

00:39:43.936 --> 00:39:46.116 A:middle
Once I've painted kind
of on top of this,

00:39:46.116 --> 00:39:48.926 A:middle
it starts to make
it feel more graphic

00:39:48.926 --> 00:39:51.836 A:middle
and make it feel a
bit more painterly

00:39:51.836 --> 00:39:53.946 A:middle
and less creature-shop.

00:39:54.636 --> 00:39:58.556 A:middle
I'm just trying to get
in some of these folds.

00:39:59.366 --> 00:40:02.936 A:middle
I'm going to get some
great crow's feet

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:39:59.366 --> 00:40:02.936 A:middle
I'm going to get some
great crow's feet

00:40:02.936 --> 00:40:03.556 A:middle
on the side of her face.

00:40:03.866 --> 00:40:06.096 A:middle
It's funny because, shaders,
we always love to work

00:40:06.096 --> 00:40:09.396 A:middle
on old characters because their
faces really tell a story.

00:40:10.306 --> 00:40:13.176 A:middle
You can see, you know, the most
common expression a person has

00:40:13.176 --> 00:40:13.986 A:middle
had for their whole life.

00:40:14.616 --> 00:40:17.346 A:middle
You know, if you frown a
lot, those lines are kind

00:40:17.346 --> 00:40:19.206 A:middle
of etched permanently
into your face.

00:40:19.846 --> 00:40:23.186 A:middle
And with older characters,
I actually get to take part

00:40:23.186 --> 00:40:25.886 A:middle
in telling the story by what
the character looks like.

00:40:26.006 --> 00:40:29.816 A:middle
And that was-- you know, my goal
here is I-- with Hardscrabble,

00:40:29.816 --> 00:40:33.386 A:middle
I really wanted her to look
as good as this character was,

00:40:33.386 --> 00:40:35.046 A:middle
I mean, because she's
such an awesome character

00:40:35.046 --> 00:40:38.596 A:middle
and I really wanted to take
part in telling that story

00:40:38.596 --> 00:40:41.456 A:middle
and make her look visually
as cool as I possibly could.

00:40:42.106 --> 00:40:45.546 A:middle
So this is good enough for
now, a good starting point.

00:40:45.546 --> 00:40:47.906 A:middle
So I've painted into
this bump channel.

00:40:48.566 --> 00:40:52.056 A:middle
And I can actually take
that channel and start

00:40:52.056 --> 00:40:53.466 A:middle
to use it in the color.

00:40:53.466 --> 00:40:55.636 A:middle
So when I visit that
channel here,

00:40:55.636 --> 00:40:57.786 A:middle
I can multiply the color
just like in Photoshop.

00:40:58.106 --> 00:41:00.276 A:middle
And we can start to see how
it will affect the final look

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:40:58.106 --> 00:41:00.276 A:middle
And we can start to see how
it will affect the final look

00:41:00.276 --> 00:41:00.836 A:middle
of the character.

00:41:01.286 --> 00:41:02.636 A:middle
But there's a whole
lot of other channels

00:41:02.666 --> 00:41:05.716 A:middle
that are needed for
the final look.

00:41:05.896 --> 00:41:07.626 A:middle
The first is the
specular channel.

00:41:07.626 --> 00:41:10.306 A:middle
What this is, and I'm not going
to bother painting it today,

00:41:10.776 --> 00:41:14.976 A:middle
what this is, is it's showing
where the shininess is,

00:41:14.976 --> 00:41:16.076 A:middle
if that makes any sense.

00:41:16.076 --> 00:41:17.186 A:middle
It's showing what
parts are going

00:41:17.186 --> 00:41:18.866 A:middle
to be shinier than other parts.

00:41:19.276 --> 00:41:21.456 A:middle
And then the roughness channel,
which makes it even less sense,

00:41:21.456 --> 00:41:23.386 A:middle
is showing how glossy

00:41:23.386 --> 00:41:26.206 A:middle
or how rough those specular
highlights are going to be.

00:41:26.966 --> 00:41:30.496 A:middle
Now, as an artist, these
things don't make a whole lot

00:41:30.496 --> 00:41:31.476 A:middle
of sense to me visually.

00:41:31.476 --> 00:41:33.316 A:middle
I look at this gray
and I'm like, "OK.

00:41:33.976 --> 00:41:35.636 A:middle
What does that mean, right?

00:41:35.636 --> 00:41:36.496 A:middle
Her eyes are black.

00:41:36.496 --> 00:41:39.566 A:middle
Her lips are a slightly
darker gray than her skin.

00:41:39.606 --> 00:41:40.856 A:middle
Her color is this other gray.

00:41:41.266 --> 00:41:44.506 A:middle
I don't know how that
affects the final look."

00:41:44.506 --> 00:41:47.076 A:middle
And before a program like
MARI, I would have to load

00:41:47.076 --> 00:41:49.516 A:middle
up these channels as
individual flattened images

00:41:49.796 --> 00:41:51.016 A:middle
in a program like Photoshop.

00:41:51.356 --> 00:41:54.956 A:middle
I'd paint the gray her of her
lips and hope that it was going

00:41:54.956 --> 00:41:57.116 A:middle
to be the right shade of gray.

00:41:57.116 --> 00:41:58.866 A:middle
And then I'd kick off a render,

00:41:58.996 --> 00:42:01.856 A:middle
and that render would take
anywhere from two minutes

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:41:58.996 --> 00:42:01.856 A:middle
and that render would take
anywhere from two minutes

00:42:01.856 --> 00:42:05.016 A:middle
for a really kind of
inexpensive render

00:42:05.016 --> 00:42:07.306 A:middle
that shows me a vague idea
of what it's going to look

00:42:07.306 --> 00:42:11.036 A:middle
like to a full 12-hour render if
I'm going into the actual shot

00:42:11.036 --> 00:42:13.166 A:middle
from the film with all of the
lighting and all the bells

00:42:13.166 --> 00:42:14.046 A:middle
and whistles turned on.

